ness; Black feminist depictions of Black and Native erotics; Black fungibility as a critique of discourses of labor exploitation; and Black art that rewrites conceptions of the human. In outlining the convergences and disjunctions between Black and Native thought and aesthetics, King identifies the potential to create new epistemologies, lines of critical inquiry, and creative practices.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aAfrican American philosophy. 0aAfrican AmericansxHistoryxMethodology. 0aAfrican AmericansxRace identity. 0aAfrican AmericansxRelations with Indians. 0aBlacksxAmericaxHistoryxMethodology. 0aBlacksxRace identityzAmerica. 0aBlackszAmericaxRace identityxPhilosophy. 0aBlackszNorth AmericaxHistoryxMethodology. 0aIndian philosophyzNorth America. 0aIndians of North AmericaxEthnic identity 0aIndians of North AmericaxEthnic identity. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2019z978311069632540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478005681zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478005681423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781478005681.jpg  a978-3-11-069632-5  DUK eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles